      • findSubRelationinFundamental

        public java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String> findSubRelationinFundamental(java.util.Hashtable<java.lang.Integer,java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String[]>> newRelTable,
                                                                 java.util.Hashtable<java.lang.String,java.util.Hashtable<java.lang.Integer,java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.String[]>>> AllFundamentalTable,
                                                                 MRepositoryManager mrmb)
        Rules in the database that can be translated into continuous paths, in a FR format style can be spotted at the paths of the FRs. This method takes a rule path and compares it with the paths of the fundamental Relationships. This means that the rule path must exist in identical form , or be part of an OR statement of the FR path, or exist without transitivity. The algorithm followed is the same as for the identification of subrelations in FR relations. The different paths are created by split at ORs at subjects, not ORs at properties. BUT in this case we don't check if the properties used in rules are subproperties of the ones in the FRs but the reverse; the properties used in the rules must be identical with or super-properties of the ones in the FRs. Also we don't read the local rules file, because we want to check for new rule entries, thus we want to find paths that could be replaces by rules, not paths that are already replaces by rules
        Parameters:
        newRelTable - a table with the list of the triples of each subpath of the new relationship
        AllFundamentalTable - a table with the list of the triples of each subpath for each fundamental relationship
        mrmb -
        Returns:
        the filename of the fundamental relationship to which the new relationship is subrelationship, or null if it is not a subrelationship of any
